Regarding the Pope's cross at Auschwitz -- which camp is it outside? Camp I, II or III? If it is at Camp I (where the museum is), I might point out that few Jews were murdered at Camp I, they were mostly murdered at Camp II. Most of the people murdered at Camp I were Poles (i.e. Catholics) or Soviet POWs. How then can it be disrespectful to Jews to put a cross up outside a camp that was used mainly to kill Catholics and other non-Jews? -- SJK----I don't know how camps were numerated, but it was placed it this camp which was made in ex-barracks (the oldest one).It is disrespectful, because the policy of Auschwitz museum was: "no religious symbols", and Catholic fundamentals put this crosswithout asking or informing anyone, even museum council. Moreover, tt was rather political than religious initiative,and using Auschwitz for politics isn't very respectful for those who died there. Taw----: Polish law places Protestant, Catholic, Orthodox, and Jewish communities on the same legal footing.::Not really. Catholic Church has a lot of priviledges that no other religious group has. Taw----The article text is duplicated in a big part. As there are minor differences, that I don't feel able to resolve, I would like to ask somebody to remove the duplication. Matusz 14:29, 1 Oct 2003 (UTC)----IMO the section "Threats to religious freedom" has nothing to do with the topic.Antisemitism is totally separate issue. It is not about the rights of Jews to practice their religion (what actually "religious freedom" means). It about the Jews as people. Therefore the section should be moved elsewhere. At least it shouldn't be the very top of the article. It is against the logical structure of encyclopedias. Mikkalai 17:19, 4 Dec 2003 (UTC):I don't follow your logic. Anti-Semitism is, by definition, an infringement on the ability of Jews to practice Judaism.:: By whose definition? My logic is within wikipedia. If you really want to follow my logic, please read Anti-semitism, Roots of anti-Semitism, and Religious freedom first. Simply put, antisemitism is an extremely acute, multirooted form of xenophobia. If you really want to discuss the issue with me further, I suggest to continue the talk on my personal page. Mikkalai 18:17, 5 Dec 2003 (UTC):A synagogue in my own town was fire-bombed last year. It was an anti-Semitic act, and the Arab immigrant perpetrators who were caught admitted this. Back in the early 1990s, New York City policemen told me ''not'' to wear a yarmulka in certain neighborhoods, because of anti-Semitic black mobs that beat up Jews by the dozen.  Last week in New York a Jewish neighborhood was covered in swastikas. All this restricts the right of Jews to worship; we are afraid to practice our own faith when people beat us up, paint swastikas, and bomb our houses of worship. Just look at at the anti-Semitic arsons against Temples and bombings if Temples in England, Turkey and Israel. It is literally impossible to separate anti-Semitism from religious discrimination. RK 13:16, Dec 5, 2003 (UTC)::It is possible, if you knew the history of Jews (it could be difficult though). But do you really think punks and skinheads really care about God? Desecration is just the way to hit harder, rather than "to restrict the right of Jews to worship", just like pogroms were *not* about "to restrict the right of Jews to own property". Mikkalai 18:17, 5 Dec 2003 (UTC)----I've moved a large block of unformatted Polish text out of the article - it's a list of names of religious dominations but even so I don't think it's helpful without a translation there as well. Here it is. Onebyone 00:33, 7 Feb 2004 (UTC)* ;#346;WIECKI RUCH MISYJNY "EPIFANIA"* ZRZESZENIE WOLNYCH BADACZY PISMA ;#346;WI;#280;TEGO W RZECZYPOSPOLITEJ POLSKIEJ* STOWARZYSZENIE BADACZY PISMA ;#346;WI;#280;TEGO W POLSCE* URZ;#260;D APOSTOLSKI JEZUSA CHRYSTUSA* KO;#346;CIÓ;#321; CHRZE;#346;CIJAN DNIA SOBOTNIEGO* JEDNOTA BRACI POLSKICH* KO;#346;CIÓ;#321; JEZUSA CHRYSTUSA ;#346;WI;#280;TYCH W D